                    <msContents>
                        <summary>An incomplete, <date calendar="#Gregorian" cert="medium"
                                from="1699" to="1800">possibly 18th-century</date> copy of the
                                <title>Mukātabāt-i ʻAllāmī</title> (Writings of ‘Allāmī) contains
                            correspondence of Persian émigré and eventual minister to the Mughal
                            emperor Akbar, <persName>Abū al-Faz̤l ibn Mubārak
                            (1551–1602)</persName>, posthumously compiled by his nephew, <persName
                                role="com" key="person_f4741">ʻAbd al-Ṣamad ibn Afz̤al Muḥammad (fl.
                                early 17th c)</persName> in <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari"
                                from="1606" to="1607">1015 AH (1606-07 CE)</date>. The latter
                            divided the work into three books (daftars): letters that Abu'l Fazl
                            drafted in Akbar's name, correspondence that he himself wrote to Akbar
                            and other nobility, and miscellaneous letters and prose pieces. </summary>
                        <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_958-item1">
                            <author key="person_5150639" role="crp">
                                <persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc">Abū al-Faz̤l ibn Mubārak,
                                    1551–1602</persName>; <lb/>
                                <persName xml:lang="ar">ابو الفضل ابن مبارک</persName>
                            </author>
                            <editor role="com" key="person_f4741">
                                <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">ʻAbd al-Ṣamad ibn Afz̤al Muḥammad
                                    (fl. early 17th c)</persName>; <lb/>
                                <persName xml:lang="fa">عبد الصمد ابن افضل محمد</persName>
                            </editor>
                            <title xml:lang="en" type="standard" key="work_879">Mukātabāt-i
                                ʻAllāmī</title>
                            <title xml:lang="fa" type="standard">مکتوبات علامی</title>
                            <title xml:lang="en" type="standard" key="work_879">Maktūbāt-i
                                ʻAllāmī</title>
                            <title xml:lang="fa" type="standard">مکاتبات علامی</title>
                            <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_879" type="alt"> Inshā-yi Abū
                                al-Faz̤l</title>
                            <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_879" type="alt"> انشاى ابو الفضل</title>

                            <incipit>
                                <locus from="11b" to="11b"> برگ ١۱پ (folio 11b):</locus> سلسه انتظام
                                کارگاه آفرینش که مظاهر حقیقت نمای شهود و شواهد قدرت وابسته بفرما
                                یزدائی بزرگ نهادی باید بر عالم و عالمیان ببازوی تائید گرفت و کار
                                جهان و جهانیان به نیروی قدر گشت آگاهی سامان و بر احکام تواند... </incipit>
                            <explicit><locus from="127b" to="127b"> برگ ١٢٧پ (folio 127b):</locus>
                                تمام شد دستور العمل تصنیف ابو الفیض و فیضی دیوان بادشاه جلاله
                                السلطان و اغزیته و اتصفته و الخلافته و الموه و الصویه و الاجلال ابو
                                الفتح جلال الدین بدستباری حضرت سیر دستگیر ضیا بخش هر ضمیر هر یک در
                                مندان عمخوار مسمندال حضرت برهان شاه در عهد خلیفه رحمان ناصر دوران
                                خسرو کشورستان درمان ابو المظفر محیی الدین اورنگزیب باد شاه غازی خلد
                                الله ملکه و بقلم شکست رقم تحریر تمود چون این فقیر را در مطابق کتاب
                                شد عرش(؟)‌درباره خط خوانان وارد از یخته(؟) اکثر نسخه بدستخط خود
                                نگاشته شد . تحریر فی التاریخ هفدهم ۱۷ شهر ذی القعده سنه ۱۱۰۳ هجری
                                مطابق روزه سه ۳ شنبه سنه ۳۶ جلوس والا </explicit>
                            <colophon>Completed on <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1692-07-31"
                                    >17 Ẕī al-Qa‘dah 1103 AH (31 Jul. 1692 CE)</date> equal to
                                regnal year 36 [‘Ālamgīrī].</colophon>
                            <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                            <note>For four other copies of this work under variant titles held in
                                the Rylands, see <ref
                                    target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6587"
                                        ><idno>Persian MS 110</idno></ref>, <ref
                                    target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6986"
                                    >490</ref>, <ref
                                    target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6994"
                                    >499</ref> and <ref
                                    target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_26558"
                                    >958</ref>.</note>
                        </msItem>
                    </msContents>
                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc form="codex">
                            <supportDesc material="chart">
                                <support>Textblock of two types of straight and cross-grained, externally sized and polished, <material>paper</material>, folios <locus from="1a" to="37b">1a–37b</locus> tinted dark brown and thereafter a natural buff colour.
                                    all probably handmade in the <placeName cert="high"
                                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208"
                                        >Indian subcontinent</placeName> with ~8 laid lines per cm and no
                                    discernible chain lines. </support>
                                <extent>
                                    <measure unit="folio" quantity="117">117 folios, 4 flyleaves
                                        (ff. ii + 117 + ii)</measure>. <dimensions type="leaf"
                                        unit="mm">
                                        <height>214</height>
                                        <width>150</width>
                                    </dimensions>
                                    <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                                        <height>188</height>
                                        <width>98</width>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </extent>
                                <foliation xml:id="original">Numbers commence with Hindu-Arabic
                                    numeral 11 on the first folio, folowed by 13, hence over by 11
                                    and probably incomplete.</foliation>
                                <collation>Undetermined. <catchwords>Catwords present on the lower-left corners of the b sides.</catchwords></collation>
                                <condition> Handle text with caution. In poor condition on the
                                    initial and final pages, with the initial folios <locus from="1a" to="37b">1a–37b</locus> tinted dark brown especially embrittled. </condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout columns="1" ruledLines="18" n="mistara">Written primarily in
                                    1 column with 18 lines per page.</layout>
                                <layout columns="1" ruledLines="1 9" n="mistara"> Folios <locus
                                        from="113b" to="114a">113b–114a</locus>, <locus from="115a"
                                        to="119b">115a–119b</locus>, and <locus from="123a"
                                        to="126b">123a–126b</locus> written in one colume with 1–9
                                    diagonal lines per page. All folios ruled with a <hi
                                        rend="italic">misṭarah</hi> hand guide. </layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote scope="major" script="nasta_liq" medium="ink">Written in clear
                                    <material>black</material> nasta‘līq with occasional shikastah
                                ligatures. </handNote>

                        </handDesc>
                        <additions><lb/>
                            <label>Inscription:</label> Note adjacent to the colophon by
                                Note by colophon, possibly signed by <persName
                                    xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" role="asn fmo ins ato">Jān Muḥammad
                                    Mumtaz</persName>.<lb/>
                            <label>Bookplates:</label> The <locus from="Inner_back_cover"
                                to="Inner_back_cover">left pastedown</locus>: <q xml:lang="en"
                                >Bibliotheca Lindesiana</q> with pencilled shelfmark <q
                                xml:lang="en">1/F</q>, and <q xml:lang="en"><hi rend="strikethrough"
                                    >Hamilton</hi> MSS No. <hi rend="strikethrough">675</hi></q>,
                            with the name and number crossed out and <q xml:lang="en">Persian</q>
                            and <q xml:lang="en">765</q> written aside. </additions>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding notBefore="1855" notAfter="1863">
                                <p>Probably repaired and rebound in a hybrid British-Indian style in
                                        <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7002481"
                                        key="place_7002481">Multan</placeName> for former owner
                                        <persName key="person_f830" role="fmo"
                                        change="#role-assignment">Colonel George William
                                        Hamilton</persName>.</p>
                                <p>. Unsupported resewing at two stations. Edges trimmed and twined
                                    chevron endbands worked in red and green
                                        <material>silk</material> threads over round cores at <locus
                                        from="Head" to="Head">head</locus> and <locus from="Tail"
                                        to="Tail">tail</locus>. Covered in full dark red-brown
                                    goatskin <material>leather</material>, tight-backed, with
                                    squares at the edges, defined joints, but without a flap (type
                                    III binding per Déroche). Internal pastedowns of ochre-coloured
                                    paper, with hinges of the same leather, adhered over the joints
                                    and onto the flyleaves to attach the cover to the textblock.</p>
                                <decoNote type="binding">Title in yellow on <locus from="Spine"
                                        to="Spine">spine</locus>. Board exterior margins
                                    double-ruled in <material>yellow</material>.</decoNote>
                                <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                                        <height>225</height>
                                        <width>163</width>
                                        <depth>24</depth>
                                    </dimensions></p>
                                <condition>Handle binding with caution. In fair but stable
                                    condition, with exterior scuffing and cracking. </condition>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                        <sealDesc>
                            <seal type="stamp" subtype="oval">
                                <p>Obliterated but measurable <material>black</material> seal
                                    impression, intaglio-carved triple-ruled, on <locus from="127b"
                                        to="127b">127b</locus>:<lb/>
                                    <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                                        <height>11</height>
                                        <width>18</width>
                                    </dimensions></p>
                            </seal>
                        </sealDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin> Completed in the <origPlace/>
                            <origDate calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1692-07-31">17 Ẕī al-Qa‘dah
                                1103 AH (31 Jul. 1692 CE)</origDate>. </origin>

                        <provenance><p>subsequently acquired by an unidetified owner, as as per his
                                namesake seal impressed on folio <locus from="85‌a" to="85a"
                                    >85a</locus>.</p></provenance>
                        <provenance><p>Later obtained, repaired, and rebound for <persName
                                    type="supplied" key="person_f830" role="fmo"
                                    change="#role-assignment">Colonel George William Hamilton
                                    (1807-1868)</persName> who served in <placeName
                                    ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208"
                                    key="place_7000208">India</placeName>
                                <date calendar="#Gregorian" from="1823" to="1867"> from 1823 to
                                    1867</date>, latterly as Commissioner in <placeName
                                    ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001535"
                                    key="place_7001535">Delhi</placeName>. He acquired over a
                                thousand Indian and Persian manuscripts, from which the <orgName
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/134857252">British Museum</orgName>
                                purchased 352 from his widow, <persName key="person_f8470"
                                    role="fmo">Charlotte Logie Hamilton (1817–1893)</persName>, now
                                held in the <orgName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/121814978">British
                                    Library</orgName>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance><p>
                                <persName role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/"
                                    key="person_97751058"> Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford
                                    (1812–1880)</persName> purchased the remainder of Hamilton's
                                collection in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1868">1868</date>
                                for his <orgName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/295427552"
                                    key="person_295427552">Bibliotheca Lindesiana</orgName> at Haigh
                                Hall, <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010384"
                                    key="place_7010384">Wigan</placeName>. </p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                                    change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName>
                                in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from
                                    <persName role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/"
                                    key="person_9985420">James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of
                                    Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>Bequeathed by <persName key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup"
                                    >Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                                    calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908">1908</date> to the <orgName
                                    type="corporation" role="rps"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands
                                    Library</orgName>, <placeName
                                    ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010477"
                                    key="place_7010477">Manchester</placeName>.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
